{{Construct analysis |text=burden of taxation |informalanalysis=This N(S)of N(T) construct expresses an entity-to-entity role mapping within the TAXATION IS A BURDEN metaphor, namely that between the 'burden' role in the Burden frame, and 'tax' role in the Taxation frame.
To 'automatically' identify the role-filler relations involved here, it seems like we would have to associate the LUs to their relevant frame roles (e.g. burden.n, load.n would be linked to 'burden' role of Burden frame).
Note that both of the 'N' constituents can be modified, e.g 'heavy burden of unfair taxation' |comment=This mapping can also be expressed using the NP(T)copula NP(S) cxn (e.g. Taxes are a burden) |Entered by=Ellen |Status=in development |construction=N_of_N |cxncomments=We need to define which subcase of N_of_N this is. It may be that it is exclusively metaphorical (unlike, e.g. Part_of_whole, or Container_of_Contents N_of_N cxns). |constituents={{CA constituent |constituent.string=burden |constituent.frames=Burden }}{{CA constituent |constituent.string=of }}{{CA constituent |constituent.string=taxation |constituent.frames=Taxation }} |bindings= |metaphors= |examples= }}

{{Construct analysis |text=burden of taxation |informalanalysis=This N(S)of N(T) construct expresses an entity-to-entity role mapping within the TAXATION IS A BURDEN metaphor, namely that between the 'burden' role in the Burden frame, and 'tax' role in the Taxation frame.
To 'automatically' identify the role-filler relations involved here, it seems like we would have to associate the LUs to their relevant frame roles (e.g. burden.n, load.n would be linked to 'burden' role of Burden frame).
Note that both of the 'N' constituents can be modified, e.g 'heavy burden of unfair taxation' |comment=This mapping can also be expressed using the NP(T)copula NP(S) cxn (e.g. Taxes are a burden) |Entered by=Ellen |Status=in development |construction=N_of_N |cxncomments=We need to define which subcase of N_of_N this is. It may be that it is exclusively metaphorical (unlike, e.g. Part_of_whole, or Container_of_Contents N_of_N cxns). |constituents={{CA constituent |constituent.string=burden |constituent.frames=Burden }}{{CA constituent |constituent.string=of }}{{CA constituent |constituent.string=taxation |constituent.frames=Taxation }} |bindings= |metaphors={{CA metaphor |metaphor.metaphor=TAXATION IS A BURDEN |metaphor.evokingsourceelements=Burden |metaphor.evokingtargetelements=Taxation }} |examples= }}

{{Construct analysis |text=burden of taxation |informalanalysis=This N(S)of N(T) construct expresses an entity-to-entity role mapping within the TAXATION IS A BURDEN metaphor, namely that between the 'burden' role in the Burden frame, and 'tax' role in the Taxation frame.
To 'automatically' identify the role-filler relations involved here, it seems like we would have to associate the LUs to their relevant frame roles (e.g. burden.n, load.n would be linked to 'burden' role of Burden frame).
Note that both of the 'N' constituents can include modifiers, e.g 'heavy burden of unfair taxation' |comment=This mapping can also be expressed using the NP(T)copula NP(S) cxn (e.g. Taxes are a burden) |Entered by=Ellen |Status=in development |construction=N_of_N |cxncomments=We need to define which subcase of N_of_N this is. It may be that it is exclusively metaphorical (unlike, e.g. Part_of_whole, or Container_of_Contents N_of_N cxns). |constituents={{CA constituent |constituent.string=burden |constituent.frames=Burden }}{{CA constituent |constituent.string=of }}{{CA constituent |constituent.string=taxation |constituent.frames=Taxation }} |bindings= |metaphors={{CA metaphor |metaphor.metaphor=TAXATION IS A BURDEN |metaphor.evokingsourceelements=Burden |metaphor.evokingtargetelements=Taxation }} |examples= }}
